<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-336-435  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 336 435.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Feb 13 1989 n235 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Let Congress sort out local-loop issues. (Perspective) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rice, James C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local information distribution services are no longer wondering iffiber optics will penetrate the local distribution market, buthow, when and by whom.andP;  The two previously separate and distinctindustries vying to be the first to offer fiber optic services,cable television (CATV) system operators and local telephonecompanies, have been joined by two other entrants, CATVoverbuilders and metropolitan area network firms.andP;  Factors thatwill influence who, how and when the communications local-loopbottleneck will be alleviated include: the pace of technologicalchange, consumer desires, the introduction of new products andservices and the legal and regulatory framework by which themarket is structured.andP;  Congress must now do its part, establishingrules facilitating fair competition and allowing the forces ofcompetition to finish the job of rewiring the nation'stelecommunication infrastructure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationMetropolitan Area NetworksTelephone CompaniesCable TVTelecommunicationsCommunications Service SuppliersFiber OpticsMarket PenetrationLocal Communication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>